HEADWORD: Rondo
<hw>Ron"do</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.
<ets>rond⟦ograve⟧</ets>, fr. F. <ets>rondeau</ets>. See
<er>Rondeau</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A
composition, vocal or instrumental, commonly of a lively, cheerful
character, in which the first strain recurs after each of the other
strains.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>Rondo</xex>-form was the earliest and
most frequent definite mold for musical construction.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Grove.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Poetry)</fld> <def>See <er>Rondeau</er>,
1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

